How is gambling for March Madness represented over time?

by Julia Moeurn

In this case, we observe how much has the gambling bets increased over time for March Madness, and in particular, the total money bet in Las Vegas Sportsbook was analyzed to see how much of a change there has been.

#mean and standard deviation of Amount Bet on March Madness
Bet <- c(122313375.8, 136707368.42, 156422264.88, 182615803.81, 191171631.21, 174793893.13, 211248677.25, 205224043.72, 230928281.46, 259426847.66, 274831858.41, 300225806.45, 337788235.29, 351808012.49)
mean(Bet)
## [1] 223964721
sd(Bet)
## [1] 71915334
Year <- c(2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017)

#correlation of Amount Bet on March Madness
cor.test(Year, Bet)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Year and Bet
## t = 15.723, df = 12, p-value = 2.267e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9255985 0.9927576
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9765773

mean: 223964721

SD: 71915334

Correlation: 0.9765773

df <- data.frame(Bet, Year)
ggplot(df, aes(x = Year , y = Bet)) +
geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Amount of Bet on March Madness") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Amount of Bet (in dollars)")

With r = 0.9765773, the amount of bet each year is highly and positively correlated; thus, with each upcoming year we would expect an increase in the amount of bet.

What is the average score that the winning teams score in the championship game?

by Anthony Lien

For this, we look at the the final scores of the championship games to find out what is the score that winning teams score on average.

# sample statistics
Score <- c(89, 82, 64, 81, 82, 75, 73, 84, 75, 89, 61, 53, 67, 82, 60, 68, 77, 71, 79, 85)
Year2 <- c(2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019)

mean(Score)
## [1] 74.85
median(Score)
## [1] 76
sd(Score)
## [1] 10.09051

mean: 74.85

median: 76

SD: 10.09051

df2 <- data.frame(Score, Year2)
ggplot(df2, aes(x = Year2 , y = Score, fill = Year2)) +
geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Winning Team Score",
       x = "Year", y = "Score (in points)")

In the years of 2000 to 2019, the winning teams of the NCAA championship scored an average of about 74.85 points (median: about 76 points) with a standard deviation of roughly 10.09051 points.

In the case that a winning team scores less than 50 points, the probability of that occuring could be calculated through a probability distribution plot as such:

x <- seq(25.15, 124.55, 0.01)

y <- dnorm(x, mean = 74.85, sd = 10.09051)

df <- data.frame(x,y)

bell <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_line() + 
  theme_classic() + 
  xlab("Score (in points)") +
  ylab("probabiliity")

shade <- rbind( c(min(x), 0), subset(df, x < 50), c(50, 0))

bell +
  ggtitle("Winning Team Score (Score < 50)") +
  geom_polygon(data = shade, aes(x,y), fill = "blue")

\[P(Score < 50)\] The probability that a winning team scores less than 50 points in the championship game is 0.0069.

How much does the viewership of the March Madness championship differ from that of the NBA finals?

by Minhyuk Kim

Here we look at the average viewership of the NCAA championship compared to the average viewership of each game of the NBA finals.

#mean and standard deviation of NCAA chmapionship viewership
ncaa <- c(20.587, 23.97, 23.686, 18.573, 17.088, 23.895, 17.543, 19.563, 19.501, 17.649, 23.944, 20.055, 20.896, 23.426, 21.196, 28.263, 17.752, 22.998, 16.5)
mean(ncaa)
## [1] 20.89921
sd(ncaa)
## [1] 3.127989
#mean and standard deviation of average NBA finals viewership
nba <- c(17.9275, 18.982, 15.6675, 9.827, 17.968, 12.62, 12.96, 9.29, 14.903, 14.286, 18.1357, 17.3933, 16.848, 17.4743,  15.544, 19.9433, 20.2829, 20.432, 17.5575)
mean(nba)
## [1] 16.21274
sd(nba)
## [1] 3.242366
#ggplot for NCAA
Y <- c(2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018)
df <- data.frame(ncaa, Y)
ggplot(df, aes(x = Y, y = ncaa, fill = Y)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "NCAA Championship Viewership",
      x = "Year", y = "viewership (in millions)") 

#ggplot for NBA
df2 <- data.frame(nba, Y)
ggplot(df2, aes(x = Y , y = nba, fill = Y)) +
geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "NBA Finals Viewership",
       x = "Year", y = "viewership (in millions)")

mean (NCAA) = 20.89921

SD (NCAA) = 3.127989

mean (NBA) = 16.21274

SD (NBA) = 3.242366

The difference in average viewership of the NCAA championship compared to the average viewership of the NBA final games is roughly 4.68647 million. This would mean that the NCAA championship garners a much larger viewership in its championship game on average compared to the viewership of the NBA finals game.
